outcomes.title: Statistical Studies
outcomes.description: I can analyze information about statistical studies.
outcomes.template:
Scenario:

A recent poll was looking to find out what American adults think about electric vehicles. The pollsters attempted to contact {{population}} American adults from June 3rd to the 4th, 2024, of which {{sample}} responded. Of the poll participants, {{result}}% say they think electric vehicles are the future of the auto industry.

What is the population that this study is trying to get information about?

The population for a survey is the entire group that the researchers are wanting information about. In this case, the pollsters are interested in finding out about American adults, so American adults is the population.

What is the sample?

The sample for a survey is the individuals that responded to the survey, not the original number of individuals contacted. In this case it is the {{sample}} American adults that were polled.

What is the variable used for this study?

The variable is whether or not a U.S. adult thinks that electric vehicles are the future of the auto industry. Remember that variables are measured on individuals, not groups. Descriptions of a variable are always in terms of something measured about an individual in the group. For example, in this case it would not be what "American Adults think" but rather what "an American adult thinks" about whether electric vehicles are the future of the auto industry. Be careful not to confuse the goal of the study with what is actually being measured.

What type of variable is the variable in question 3?

What someone thinks is a Categorical variable. It would be described by words, or possibly on a numerical scale representing words, for example 1 = disagree. It is not something that can be represented as a number that makes sense to do arithmetic operations on.

What is the sample statistic for this study?

The sample statistic is {{result}}% of those polled think that electric vehicles are the future of the auto industry. A sample statistic is a known numerical value about the group of individuals in the sample.

What is the parameter of interest for this study? (the population parameter that the pollsters are trying to gather information about)

The parameter of interest is what percentage of American adults think electric vehicles are the future of the auto industry. A population parameter is a numerical value or summary number that the researchers are trying to estimate using a sample statistic.

outcomes.title: Sample, Bias, and Variability
outcomes.description: I can identify and analyze key elements of samples including bias and variability.
outcomes.template:
Scenario:

The county of Los Angeles wants to get an idea of how residents feel about the quality of the transportation options in the county. In order to get the information, they use records of vehicles registered in the county to randomly select 1,000 residents of the county to send them a questionnaire written in English, asking for them to reply to a variety of questions about the transportation option available in the county.

Survey respondents were asked to decide to what degree they agreed with the following statements. The possible answers were "Strongly Agree", "Agree", "Neither Agree or Disagree", "Disagree", "Strongly Disagree".

The county has done a wonderful job providing excellent transportation options to county residents.

There is sufficient parking in the county.

{{sample}} residents responded to the survey. {{result_1}}\% of respondents said that they {{agree_1}} that there are sufficient transportation options available and {{result_2}}\% said that they {{agree_2}} that there is sufficient parking.

Does the above use a sampling frame? If so, what is the sampling frame?

A sampling frame is the source list from which a sample is drawn. In this case, yes, there is a sampling frame being used. The sampling frame is owners of vehicles registered in the county. A complete answer to this question should clearly answer the question asked (Does the above use a sampling frame) AND be specific about what that frame is.

What is the sampling method used in the above scenario? Explain.

The sampling method was a simple random sample or SRS since all owners of vehicles registered in the county have an equal chance of being selected. The problem states that the County Department of Transportation uses the vehicle registration records to "randomly select 1000 residents of the county". To answer this question, you need to know the six different sampling methods we have talked about in class (simple random, stratified, voluntary response, convenience, and cluster) and how to distinguish between them. The complete answer includes not only the method but what evidence from the problem demonstrates that this is the sampling method.

Looking at the sampling frame and the sampling method, would the sample be a valid sample or is it likely to be a biased sample? Explain why.

The sample method is valid but the sampling frame is like to produce a biased sample. Since the sampling frame doesn't match the population, and since the sampling frame relates to transportation which is also what is being investigated in the survey, this is likely to introduce bias. The sampling frame leaves out people who don't have a car, and are therefore the most reliant on transportation options provided by the county. People reliant on public transportation could quite easily feel very different about the quality of the transportation options provided to county residents. This undercoverage of people reliant on public transportation therefore results in a sample that is not representative of the population, hence a biased sample.

Identify potential sources of bias other then the sampling method and sampling frame from the information given and explain why they lead to bias (Only use the information given, do not speculate about information not provided).

The sample was given only in English. If you have a large proportion of residents in the county that don't speak English they are likely to be left out of the sample and therefore not covered in the responses to the survey. HOWEVER, if the proportion of residents in the county who don't speak English is small then this is unlikely to be a source of bias. So rather than automatically saying that a restriction is language is a likely source of bias, you need to analyze the size of the group that would be excluded. Other than the language, the wording of the first statement is very problematic. Using words like "wonderful" and "excellent" can bias responses because people like to agree with others, and those words are ones that people would often like to agree with. Alternatively, even if someone feels that the transportation options are ok, one person's "wonderful" might not match another person's "wonderful". Other potential sources of bias for this type of non-sampling bias could include measurement or processing errors, although there is no evidence of these in this particular problem. As you answer problems like these, you need to look at what you KNOW (for example the wording of the statements), not what you DON'T know (like anything about the measurement or processing of this survey).

If the county did the survey again, would you expect that exactly {{result_2}}\% of respondents would {{agree_2}} that there is sufficient parking in the county? Why or why not?

No, the exact same result would not be expected due to the variability that arises from taking different samples from a population. A complete answer to this question should reference the statistical background that demonstrates an understanding of the variability that arises due to sampling. Remember that sample statistics often vary from sample to sample and are usually not exactly equal to the population parameter. A sample statistic can accidentally exactly equal the population parameter, but often it is slightly different. In the case where you have a biased sample, the variation can be extreme. A complete answer to this question not only mentions sampling variability but draws from the specific scenario. In this case, you might say "Since a new sample would like contain different vehicle owners and might also have a different number of people responding, the proportion who would respond this way would likely be different"

Based on the results of this survey, can the county of Los Angeles be sure that they understand how residents feel about the quality of public transportation options that are available to them in the county?

No, this survey contains too much bias. A complete answer here would reference back to the types of bias in the problem and would include specifics about how the bias prevents the county from being confident in their understanding. For example, since they only sampled from among car owners, car owners might feel differently about how much parking there is compared to people who rely primarily on public transportation.

outcomes.title: Experimental Studies
outcomes.description: I can identify and analyze key elements of experiments.
outcomes.template:
Scenario:

A new study suggests that "Pink Drinks can help you run faster and further." Researchers investigated the effect of drink color on exercise performance. In this study, {{n}} active {{age}} were instructed to run for 30 minutes on a treadmill. Half of the participants used a pink drink to rinse their mouths during the run, the other half used a clear drink to rinse their mouths during the run. The drinks were identical except for color. The participants were randomized as to which drink they received. The researchers evaluating the performance of the participants {{blinding}}. Researchers noted the speed each participant selected for their run and asked participants to rate their feelings of pleasure from the drink. {{results}}

Describe the control group.

The half of the {{n}} {{age}} that rinsed with a clear drink

What is the explanatory variable?

The pink color of the drink

What were the response variables?

The distance covered and the feeling of pleasure from the drink

Did the researchers use any blinding? If so, what was blinded? Explain your answer.

{{answer_4}}. Explanation needed.

Are the results generalizable to all adults? Explain your answer.

No. Explanation needed, student explanations will vary.

data.results: Self-selected running speed and expressed feelings of pleasure were significantly improved for participants using the pink mouth rinse

outcomes.title: Statistical Graphs
outcomes.template:
A critical component to our understanding of statistics is being able to read and understand graphs. It is also critical that we be able to look at graphs and identify any flaws they might have. Be sure to answer ALL the questions.

Who is wearing face covering in public?

Use the graph above to answer the questions.

What type of graph is this?

The is a line graph or a time series graph. A line graph is where the data is displayed as points connected by lines. Many (if not most) line graphs are actually time series graphs. Time series graphs display data over a period of time and can be identified by a horizontal access marked as time (often dates).

What data is being represented on the x- and y- axes of the graph?

The x-axis is time and the y-axis is percent of people wearing mask in public. The x-axis is shown in months and the y-axis is percentages with the tick marks at intervals of 25%.

What data does the {{color_3}} line represent? Be sure to give the real world context for your answer.

The percentage of people wearing face coverings in public in {{answer_3}} from February to July. Be sure to connect your answer to the real world and not just to a mathematical or statistical description. In this case, "the percent is going up" would not be considered sufficient. The percent of what (people wearing face coverings in public) where (in the specified county) is doing what (increasing, decreasing, etc.)

Compare {{country_4a}} and {{country_4b}} in {{month_4}}. What is happening?

{{answer_4}}. Also with this question, the real world context is critical. Describing "lines" and other mathematical and statistical objects is not the point. The actual real world context is what we need to see.

Explain why the Japan line is so short compared to the other lines.

The data wasn't available; wasn't collected; or wasn't shared. Be careful not to include assumptions about WHY the data isn't there, or assumptions that missing data is the same as 0%. If there is something missing from a graph, the only thing you can conclude is that the data is not available or was not collected or shared.

What is the overall trend in the UK from May to July? Be sure to include real world context.

outcomes.title: Correlation and Regression
outcomes.description: I can use correlation and regression to describe relationships between two variables in a set of data.
outcomes.template:
The Scenario:

In 2019, a group of researchers collected the data from a sample of 222 car models and looked at the impact of different characteristics of the cars on the MSRP (manufacturers’ suggested retail price). They ran a regression analysis. The scatterplots and regression lines are shown below for MSRP vs HP (horsepower) and MSRP vs Engine size (in liters).

Below is the information about the regression model for the scatter plot above.

Equation and R^2 value for the manufacturers' suggested retail price (MSRP) vs horsepower (HP).

MSRP = -3162.10 + 168.64 * HP

The R^2 value for this regression model is 0.582

Below is the information about the regression model for the scatter plot above.

Equation and R^2 value for the manufacturers' suggested retail price (MSRP) vs engine size (in liters)

MSRP = 18017.87 + 7976.67 * Engine size

The R^2 value for this regression model is 0.193

Use the two scatter plots and the given information about the regression models to answer the questions below.

Which model, if any, would you use to predict the price of a car? Explain why your choice would be the best model to get an accurate prediction.

MSRP vs HP is the better model to make predictions with. To explain which regression model is better, there are several options. One is to look at which has a stronger correlation, R. Note that "stronger" refers to being closer to 1 or -1. The closer a correlation is to 1 or -1, the stronger it is. Conversely, the closer to 0 a correlation is, the weaker it is. Another option is to look at R-squared. Because R is the square root of R-squared, a stronger R is the same as having the higher R-squared. Finally, if for some reason you don't actually know what R or R-squared are, you can look at the graph to see which model has the dots on the scatterplot more packed together into a line. In this case, the R-squared (R^2) value is higher for MSRP vs HP when compared to the one for MSRP vs Engine size. This means that the correlation coefficient, R, for MSRP vs HP is closer to either 1 or -1 when compared to the correlation coefficient for MSRP vs Engine size. In order to explain your answers for this standard, it is important to put all your answers into the real world context of the problem.

What do you predict the MSRP of a vehicle with {{HP}} HP to be? Explain why you used the model you did and show all work. Put your final answer into a complete sentence to answer the question.

${{answer_2}}. One of the most common mistakes made when computing this prediction is to use your calculator incorrectly. Remember that your calculator needs you to give it the correct order of operations. So either use extra parentheses in your calculator, or do the multiplication first. Additionally, don't forget to put your final answer into a sentence - The predicted MSRP of a vehicle whose horsepower is {{HP}} is ${{answer_2}}.

Would you use one of the regression models to predict the MSRP of a vehicle with an engine size of 3.2 liters? Why or why not?

No, the model has a weak correlation. Remember that there are two reasons NOT to use a regression model. Either the correlation is too weak (usually something under 0.4) or the value for which you are trying to make a prediction is outside the range of the data. Note - this does NOT mean that it is outside the range of the GRAPH. It is possible to have a value that is in the range of the graph (if you have a long axis) but that is still outside the range of the DATA. In this case, the correlation is well below 0.4 so that is the main reason.

There is a dot at ({{point_4x}}, {{point_4y}}) on the MSRP vs horsepower graph. Explain what this dot represents in context of the study.

A specific car in the dataset with {{point_4x}} horsepower and a MSRP of ${{point_4y}}. Dots on a scatterplot represent individuals in the dataset. In this case, the dataset is made up of cars. The values on the scatterplot are two quantitative values about ONE car. So on the MSRP vs horsepower graph it is the MSRP and horsepower of a specific car. For the MSRP vs Engine Size graph it is the MSRP and Engine Size of a specific car. Make sure when you describe the point that you include any units and correctly associate the x-coordinate with the meaning of the data on the x-axis and the y-coordinate with the meaning of the data on the y-axis.

Compute the correlation coefficient, R, for the MSRP vs horsepower model. Explain the meaning of R in the context of the scenario.

0.7629, there is a strong positive relationship between horsepower and MSRP so as the horsepower goes up, on average so does the MSRP. Every correlation has THREE pieces of information, the numeric value, the sign of the correlation, and the strength of the correlation. So to compute the correlation you need to get the number AND the sign. To explain the meaning you need to talk about the strength and direction of the correlation, and what it means in terms of the variables in the dataset.
